		<div id="comment-318">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/8882151e2f68447b4bc641f6fd72c87e?s=40&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/8882151e2f68447b4bc641f6fd72c87e?s=80&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn"><a href='../../index.html' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Kevin Standlee</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
				
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="index.html#comment-318">
				March 14, 2009 at 11:26					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

				<div class="comment-body"><p>Ian:</p>
<p>We cannot speak to the specific content of individual Worldcons. Each Worldcon is separately organized by independent committees.  (Similar to how the Vancouver Olympic Committee for 2010 is not the same as the London Olympic Committee for 2012.)  The Hugo Awards <em>are</em> directly associated with Worldcon (it&#8217;s each year&#8217;s Worldcon members who choose the recipients, and the Awards themselves are administered by each Worldcon committee), but those of us who manage the Hugo Awards web site are not the same people as those who organize the individual conventions.</p>
<p>As you know, this year&#8217;s Worldcon is <a href="http://www.anticipationsf.ca/" rel="nofollow">Anticipation</a> in Montreal. I&#8217;m not sure what the confusing part of its web site is for you; however, I will pass along your message to the organizers of the convention&#8217;s <a href="http://www.anticipationsf.ca/English/Programming" rel="nofollow">programming division</a>.</p>
</div>

				<div class="reply">
				<a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='index.html?replytocom=318#respond' data-commentid="318" data-postid="11" data-belowelement="comment-318" data-respondelement="respond" aria-label='Reply to Kevin Standlee'>Reply</a>				</div><!-- .reply -->
			</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

